Chapter 3 â€” Problem Statement

3.1 Formal Problem Definition

Current rover navigation architectures assume relatively stable sensing conditions. However, sensor reliability varies across planetary environments. Let the true rover state be x, sensor observations be Z, and the environment descriptor be E. A static fusion architecture assumes:

p(x|Z) âˆ p(Z|x)p(x)

with no dependence on E. This assumption fails when:

Â· Vision degradation during dust storms (increased camera noise)
Â· Wheel slip on deformable terrain (encoder scale factor error)
Â· Illumination variability (feature detection failure)
Â· Radar noise in heterogeneous soil (multipath and clutter)

The research problem addressed in this thesis is:

How can a planetary rover autonomously estimate the environment descriptor E in real time, and use it to dynamically adapt its perception, state estimation, and navigation strategy to maximize safety and efficiency under strict energy and computational constraints?

3.2 Scope and Assumptions

Assumptions:

Â· The rover is equipped with a baseline sensor suite: stereo cameras, IMU, wheel encoders, and optionally a radar/LiDAR (massâ€‘dependent)
Â· Onboard computer has computational capacity comparable to current spaceâ€‘grade processors (RAD750 class: ~200â€“400 MIPS)
Â· Basic terrain interaction models (e.g., wheelâ€‘terrain contact mechanics) are available
Â· Environment changes occur at timescales longer than the control loop (seconds to minutes), enabling realâ€‘time adaptation

Scope:

Â· This thesis focuses on perception, state estimation, and navigation layersâ€”not lowâ€‘level motor control or highâ€‘level science goal planning
Â· Validation is conducted through simulation and analog field tests, not flight hardware integration

