Chapter 5 â€” Energyâ€‘Aware Navigation

5.1 Energy Consumption Model

Total energy consumption is modeled as:

E_total = E_motion + E_computation

where:

Â· E_motion = âˆ« P_drive(v, slope, terrain) dt
Â· E_computation = Î£_i P_i Â· t_i for each active sensor/algorithm

5.2 Terrain-Dependent Energy Cost

In extreme environments, E_motion is not merely a function of distance but of Specific Resistance derived from terramechanics. We refine the energy model by integrating Bekker-Wong parameters estimated in the Cognitive Layer:

E_motion = âˆ« [ Î¼_r(W, z) + (WÂ·sinÎ¸) + cÂ·iÂ² ] Â· v Â· dt

where:

Â· z = sinkage (estimated by Cognitive Layer)
Â· i = slip ratio
Â· W = rover weight (adjusted for gravity g)
Â· Î¼_r = rolling resistance coefficient
Â· c = terrain cohesion

5.3 Adaptive Cost Function

The navigation objective is to minimize:

J = âˆ« ( Î±Â·E_motion + Î²Â·Risk(E) + Î³Â·Time + Î´Â·Comm(E) ) dt

subject to terrain traversability and energy constraints.

Where:

Â· Î±, Î², Î³, Î´ are tunable weights
Â· Risk(E) is derived from the Cognitive Layer outputs: Risk = f(slip_probability, tipâ€‘over_probability, terrain_roughness)
Â· Comm(E) represents the expected cost of communication delays or human intervention

5.4 Risk Formulation from Learning

Slip probability is predicted using a Sparse Gaussian Process (SGP) trained online:

P(slip > Ï„ | terrain_features, slope) = GP(Î¼, ÏƒÂ²)

The GP provides both a mean prediction and uncertainty, which feeds directly into the risk term.

5.5 Computational Throttle: Perception-on-Demand

In planetary missions, the CPU is a major heat source and power consumer. SAPNA introduces Perception-on-Demand:

Â· If the Cognitive Layer identifies a Nominal regime with high confidence, the architecture downâ€‘samples computationally expensive processes
Â· Example: Reduce stereo matching frequency from 5 Hz to 1 Hz, saving significant E_computation
Â· If entering Challenging terrain, perception frequency increases automatically

The cost function explicitly accounts for this tradeâ€‘off:

E_computation = Î£_i (p_i_active Â· P_i)

where p_i_active is a continuous variable representing processing frequency/load for each sensor/algorithm.

