Chapter 6 â€” Lightweight Onboard Learning

6.1 Philosophy

Instead of large deep neural networks, SAPNA uses statistically efficient, verifiable learning methods suitable for spaceâ€‘grade processors:

Â· Online parameter adaptation
Â· Confidence estimation with built-in uncertainty quantification
Â· Incremental model updates
Â· Computational tractability on RAD750-class hardware

6.2 Sparse Gaussian Processes for Terrain Property Estimation

Standard Gaussian Processes have O(NÂ³) complexity, which would "choke" a RAD750 processor. SAPNA employs Sparse Gaussian Processes (SGPs) with inducing points, allowing the rover to maintain a global map of terrain properties using only a small subset (M â‰ª N) of representative observations.

6.2.1 Sparse GP Formulation

Given N observations, we select M inducing points X_m with corresponding outputs u. The predictive distribution becomes:

Î¼_ = K_*m K_mmâ»Â¹ u*
Ïƒ_*Â² = K_ - K_m K_mmâ»Â¹ K_m + K_m K_mmâ»Â¹ Î£ K_mmâ»Â¹ K_m**

where Î£ is the covariance of the inducing outputs. Complexity reduces to O(NMÂ²) , enabling realâ€‘time operation.

6.2.2 Application: Slip Prediction

The SGP models slip ratio as a function of:

Â· Terrain slope (from stereo reconstruction)
Â· Visual texture features (from onboard cameras)
Â· Wheel motor currents (proprioceptive feedback)

The GP provides both a mean prediction Î¼_slip and uncertainty Ïƒ_slipÂ², which feeds directly into the Risk(E) term in navigation planning.

6.3 Random Forests for Terrain Classification

For discrete terrain typing (sand, bedrock, soil, gravel), a Random Forest classifier is trained offline and adapted online via:

Â· Confidenceâ€‘weighted updates
Â· Outlier detection for novel terrain types

Random Forests are selected because they:

Â· Handle multi-modal features efficiently
Â· Provide feature importance rankings
Â· Are amenable to hardware implementation

6.4 Online Adaptation of the Reliability Map

The parameters in the Î¦_i(E) table (Chapter 4.2.4) are slowly tuned using experience:

Â· When the AEKF's innovation statistics become inconsistent (e.g., normalized innovation squared exceeds threshold), the corresponding Î¦_i(E) inflation factor is adjusted
Â· This creates a closedâ€‘loop learning system that improves model accuracy over the mission lifetime
Â· Adaptation rate is deliberately slow to maintain stability

