Appendix A: Mathematical Derivation of the AEKF Update

A.1 System Dynamics and Linearization

We define the discrete-time non-linear system dynamics and observation models as:

x_k = f(x_{k-1}, u_{k-1}) + w_{k-1},â€ƒw_k âˆ¼ ğ’©(0, Q_k)
z_{i,k} = h_i(x_k) + v_{i,k},â€ƒv_{i,k} âˆ¼ ğ’©(0, R_i(E_k))

where H_{i,k} is the Jacobian of h_i evaluated at the predicted state xÌ‚_{k|k-1}:

H_{i,k} = âˆ‚h_i/âˆ‚x |{xÌ‚{k|k-1}}

A.2 Prediction Phase

xÌ‚_{k|k-1} = f(xÌ‚_{k-1}, u_{k-1})
P_{k|k-1} = F_{k-1} P_{k-1} F_{k-1}^T + Q_{k-1}

A.3 Adaptive Measurement Update

For each sensor i, we inject the environment-conditioned penalty function Î¦_i(E_k):

R_i(E_k) = R_i_nominal Â· Î¦_i(E_k)

Innovation covariance: S_{i,k} = H_{i,k} P_{k|k-1} H_{i,k}^T + R_i(E_k)

Adaptive Kalman gain: K_{i,k} = P_{k|k-1} H_{i,k}^T S_{i,k}^{-1}

State update: xÌ‚_k = xÌ‚_{k|k-1} + Î£_i K_{i,k} (z_{i,k} - h_i(xÌ‚_{k|k-1}))

Covariance update: P_k = (I - Î£_i K_{i,k} H_{i,k}) P_{k|k-1}

A.4 Information-Theoretic Interpretation

The Information Matrix (precision) of the update is:

â„_total(E_k) = P_{k|k-1}^{-1} + Î£_i H_{i,k}^T R_i(E_k)^{-1} H_{i,k}

where the Environment-Conditioned Fisher Information is:

â„_i(E_k) = H_{i,k}^T R_i(E_k)^{-1} H_{i,k}

When environment degrades a sensor (R_i â†‘), its contribution to â„_total decreases, naturally shifting the belief to more reliable sensors. This demonstrates that SAPNA's adaptation is not heuristic but statistically optimal.

